le. The agent guidance mentions a standard Enumeratum-style pattern rather than just Scala enum, which makes me wonder if I should consider using a sealed class. However, since it mentions that Scala 3 tests are fine with enums, I should look into the \\\"source context only API guidance\\\" and check which behaviors are supported. The macro source documentation discusses finding ValueEntryType-typed objects, often with examples of case objects.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering enum cases**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether using `id.symbol.fullName` could result in binary names like \\\"pkg.TrafficSignal.Stop\\\" versus \\\"pkg.TrafficSignal$Stop,\\\" which might cause a failure. If it's a top-level class, it complicates things further. I’m considering using a Scala 3 enum at the top level, with the cases defined within it, but I wonder if this could also lead to problems with `Class.forName`. The field coverage would only be active after the class exists, which I need to keep in mind.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_50OWkRVnpK0AuZzVbDgucGGP|fc_00c2bac56877bcc5016a3e6c17b5f8819590445a78af99b389", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/com.beachape/enumeratum-macros_3/1.9.0/src/test/scala/com_beachape/enumeratum_macros_3/ValueEnumMacrosTest.scala", "edits": [{"oldText": "    val entries: IndexedSeq[TopLevelArticleStatus] = TopLevelArticleStatus.values\n", "newText": "    val entries: IndexedSeq[TopLevelArticleStatus] = discoveredTopLevelArticleStatuses\n"}, {"oldText": "object TopLevelArticleStatus {\n  val values: IndexedSeq[TopLevelArticleStatus] =\n    findTopLevelStringValueEntries[TopLevelArticleStatus]\n}\n", "newText": "object TopLevelArticleStatus {\n  val values: IndexedSeq[TopLevelArticleStatus] = discoveredTopLevelArticleStatuses\n}\n\nval discoveredTopLevelArticleStatuses: IndexedSeq[TopLevelArticleStatus] =\n  findTopLevelStringValueEntries[TopLevelArticleStatus]\n"}]}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA