[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering Scala macro compilation**\n\nI’m thinking about macro compilation and how Gradle handles source files, especially between main and test sources. If main source files are compiled before tests, we need to manage where we define our enum entries—possibly in a dependency using `enumeratum`. I've realized that I can't add dependencies or use Class.forName as needed. Perhaps I can utilize existing test fixtures from the library, but I wonder if splitting test sources into main and test could help. There's a lot to consider!\n\n**Evaluating test configurations**\n\nI'm considering the rules around creating or updating tests, specifically under the resolved target test source root, which seems limiting. I’m thinking about configuring Gradle to compile a test fixture source set prior to actual tests, potentially placing these sources in `src/test/scala`. It might also be possible to create Java or Scala sources there and set up a two-phase compile for the test Scala, though that feels a bit messy. It’s interesting how the dynamic access call interacts with singleton modules as `Ident`. So much to think about!\n\n**Considering fixture file structure**\n\nI’m thinking about how a fixture file might break the one-to-one mapping between dynamic-access report classes and the generated test class files. They want a separate Scala test file for each dynamic class, so should I keep the fixture in the same `ValueEnumMacrosTest.scala` file? But if we precompile the same file, I can't split it. Maybe I need a second file for the fixture that doesn’t have \"Test\" in the name. Would that be okay?", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_00c2bac56877bcc5016a3e6cc547d48195a7f02bfa9636abb5\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqPmzlAiC1D-ebDkBmMTNLkCdSRULoPwUTjLkBOQlJkIbRMTe-SMauh-_seIKl264NKyHfXb094Bo03S9L3Zhg9xUPwWmtlZJ-LZfI7sYw-6_FUKvPZWC